Cheney blames Davis for crisis=20
'They knew over a year ago they had a problem'=20
Zachary Coile, Chronicle Political Writer
Monday, May 21, 2001=20
,2001 San Francisco Chronicle=20
URL:=20
http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=3D/chronicle/archive/2001/05=
/21/M
N67797.DTL&type=3Dnews=20
Washington -- Vice President Dick Cheney, in his most blunt and partisan=20
assessment yet of California's energy crisis, faulted Democratic Gov. Gray=
=20
Davis for failing to act quickly enough and called the state's purchase of=
=20
nearly $6 billion worth of energy "a harebrained scheme."=20
Cheney, the administration's point man on energy issues, went on a pair of=
=20
Sunday morning news shows to help sell a national energy plan that Presiden=
t=20
Bush proposed last week. The discussion inevitably turned to California.=20
"They've bankrupted the biggest utility in the state, destroyed the state's=
=20
credit rating and squandered a significant portion of the state's financial=
=20
surplus in a harebrained scheme to try to use the state to purchase power,"=
=20
the vice president told Tim Russert of NBC's "Meet the Press."=20
A spokesman for Davis responded that the vice president's remarks yesterday=
=20
were "grossly misinformed" and meant to divert attention from the=20
administration's neglect of the state and its power woes.=20
"The Bush administration has refused to address California's problem, and n=
ow=20
they're washing their hands of it," Davis spokesman Steve Maviglio said.=20
The tit-for-tat remarks culminated a week that has seen an escalation in th=
e=20
war of words between the Democratic governor and the Republican White House=
.=20
The two administrations are increasingly engaging in a blame game as they=
=20
confront a worsening crisis with enormous political stakes for both sides.=
=20
Responding to critics -- including Davis -- who say the White House has don=
e=20
little to help California, the vice president pointed the finger back at th=
e=20
state's top Democratic official.=20
"They knew over a year ago they had a problem, and Gray Davis refused to=20
address that problem," Cheney said. "(They) kept putting it off and putting=
=20
it off and putting it off, with the notion that somehow price caps could be=
=20
maintained.=20
"Now, today, where are they in California? Well, rates are having to go up.=
=20
The PUC just had to increase the rates themselves in California. They've go=
t=20
rolling blackouts, they've had some already. They'll have them across the=
=20
state this summer," Cheney said.=20
Cheney's remarks referred to the state's purchases of almost $6 billion wor=
th=20
of energy, which began after the major utilities could no longer afford=20
skyrocketing wholesale prices for energy.=20
Earlier this month, the Democrat-controlled California Legislature approved=
 a=20
bill, opposed by GOP lawmakers, to issue $13.4 billion in bonds to repay th=
e=20
state's general fund to avoid making deep cuts in other state programs.=20
KEEPING THE LIGHTS ON
"That's the governor keeping the lights on," Maviglio said. "Because of the=
=20
failure of the federal government to act (to impose price controls), the=20
state had to move to keep the lights on."=20
Cheney's comments came just days after Davis sharply criticized Bush's ener=
gy=20
plan, saying it wouldn't help California consumers facing rising energy=20
bills.=20
"Mr. President, you didn't create this problem, but you are the only one wh=
o=20
can solve it," Davis said in a letter released to the press. "With all due=
=20
respect, Californians want to know, Mr. President, whether you're going to =
be=20
on their side."=20
Davis also suggested that by refusing to ask federal regulators for price=
=20
caps, Bush was effectively allowing price-gouging by oil and gas producers =
in=20
his home state of Texas. Cheney dismissed the allegation last week as=20
"goofy."=20
CALIFORNIA A BAD EXAMPLE
In speeches on his energy plan, the president has mostly used California as=
=20
an example to the nation of what not to do. He warned last week that the=20
state's blackouts were a preview of what other states could face if the=20
country doesn't boost energy supplies.=20
Some California Republican leaders have warned Bush, who will visit Souther=
n=20
California later this month, to soften the administration's rhetoric on the=
=20
energy crisis to avoid being seen as unsympathetic to the state's plight.=
=20
Cheney explained yesterday that the administration opposes even short-term=
=20
price controls because they could discourage energy suppliers from selling=
=20
energy into California and building more plants in the state.=20
"In the final analysis, it's going to be the private sector's response that=
=20
generates the power we're going to need long-term," Cheney said.=20
The vice president did offer an olive branch to Davis, noting that both=20
Democratic and Republican lawmakers approved the state's deregulation=20
legislation, precipitating the state's energy problems.=20
"In fairness to Governor Davis, the screwy regulatory scheme they put in=20
place was supported on both sides of the aisle out there," Cheney said. "Bu=
t=20
he was the one who was in charge when it went haywire."=20
Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., who followed Cheney on CBS' "Face the Nation"=
=20
yesterday morning, put the blame back on the White House. She recalled that=
=20
President John F. Kennedy called steel company executives into his office=
=20
when they were accused of price gouging. She urged Bush and Cheney to do th=
e=20
same with energy suppliers.=20
"You have the vice president sitting there, sounding like an oil man," Boxe=
r=20
said. "The energy companies are blameless here, he says. And the truth is=
=20
that the facts belie that.=20
"He's doing nothing in the budget to help us at all, not even a phone call =
to=20
FERC, not even a jawboning of some of the executives."=20
E-mail Zachary Coile at zcoile@sfchronicle.com




Lighting technology leading the way in energy conservation=20
Keay Davidson, Chronicle Science Writer
Monday, May 21, 2001=20
,2001 San Francisco Chronicle=20
URL:=20
http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=3D/chronicle/archive/2001/05=
/21/M
N208452.DTL&type=3Dnews=20
Imagine replacing your living-room lights with walls that gently glow, or=
=20
your plain glass windows with electronic ones that darken at the press of a=
=20
button.=20
Some day, such gee-whiz technologies might save California and the nation=
=20
plenty of energy -- besides bringing (for better or worse) the aesthetic=20
taste of the Jetsons into tomorrow's homes.=20
In the meantime, researchers are designing less futuristic energy-saving=20
gadgets that might be ready in time to help ease the energy problems=20
California is facing now.=20
Among the technologies under development: unusual ceiling lamps being teste=
d=20
in a Bay Area post office; miniature fluorescent lights that offer better=
=20
luminescence than their drab, low-glow ancestors; luminous, flexible plasti=
c=20
tubes that emit neat little beams of light; and indoor versions of the=20
brilliant sulfur lamps that presently illuminate giant parking lots at nigh=
t.=20
If the history of the past three decades is any guide, energy-saving=20
technologies aren't just wacky schemes like the flying cars and=20
atomic-powered blimps ballyhooed in 1950s editions of Popular Science and=
=20
like magazines.=20
Rather, energy-saving technologies are already an unheralded hero of late=
=20
20th century technology, having saved the nation the energy equivalent of=
=20
numerous nuclear power plants since the last "We're running out of energy!"=
=20
freakouts of the 1970s.=20
The next time your smug friends and relatives back east mock California as =
an=20
"energy hog," you can inform them that, in fact, we only use half as much=
=20
electricity per capita as the rest of the United States. A major reason:=20
prescient energy-conservation rules developed under then-Gov. Jerry Brown t=
wo=20
decades ago, according to veteran energy-conservation scientist Art=20
Rosenfeld.=20
Widely ridiculed as "Governor Moonbeam," Brown and the California Energy=20
Commission thought it was wiser to develop tough energy-conservation=20
standards for buildings and appliances than to build new nuclear power plan=
ts=20
-- "and it turns out it was," says Rosenfeld, a current member of the Energ=
y=20
Commission and former czar of energy conservation science at Lawrence=20
Berkeley National Laboratory, which is funded mainly by the U.S. Energy=20
Department.=20
Undaunted by the changing political winds of the past three decades,=20
scientists at the lab have continued designing energy-conserving=20
technologies, even though, at first glance, the new technologies don't look=
=20
that exciting.=20
NEW LIGHTING TECHNOLOGIES
Witness, for example, the lamps being tested at the post office in Rodeo. T=
he=20
lamps are long, thin tubes that aim light directly onto each carrier's=20
mail-sorting station, rather than wastefully spreading it all over the plac=
e.=20
It's a simple innovation, yet it reduces energy costs for lighting by up to=
=20
70 percent, Lawrence Berkeley researchers have calculated.=20
Likewise, they have recently invented a new type of high-performance,=20
energy-efficient table lamp that "could greatly reduce the current power=20
problems we have in California while increasing the quality of the lighting=
,"=20
says researcher Michael Siminovitch of the Berkeley lab.=20
The lamp consists of compact fluorescent lights that can be manipulated to=
=20
direct light in different directions -- toward the ceiling, for example. Th=
at=20
allows the users to fine-tune lighting conditions to their precise needs,=
=20
overcoming common complaints about the dimness and poor design of first-=20
generation power-saving lights.=20
The new lamps use only one-fourth as much energy as a 150-watt incandescent=
=20
table lamp or a 300-watt halogen lamp. Unveiled in March, they are being=20
field- tested by the lab in collaboration with the Sacramento Municipal=20
Utility District (SMUD), Southern California Edison and Pacific Gas and=20
Electric.=20
LIGHT-EMITTING DIODES
Looking farther into the future, the old-fashioned incandescent light bulb=
=20
may be challenged by electronic LEDs, or light-emitting diodes, commonly us=
ed=20
for VCRs and alarm clocks. Those dim little lights may eventually be made=
=20
bright enough, and white enough, to begin replacing traditional lighting=20
sources.=20
One problem: the refraction or bending of light. Everyone has seen what=20
happens when one inserts a straw into a glass of water -- the submerged=20
portion of the straw appears to bend. In the semiconductor materials used i=
n=20
LEDs, much of the internally generated light is bent so much that it reflec=
ts=20
back into the LED -- that is, it can't escape. Hence, present LEDs don't em=
it=20
enough light to attract a large commercial market.=20
However, engineers at Lawrence Berkeley and elsewhere are designing new LED=
s=20
that would emit far more light. One of them is physicist Steve Johnson, who=
=20
is confident that LEDs can eventually be made brighter than ordinary light=
=20
bulbs. He points out that colored LEDs are already used in some traffic=20
lights.=20
By mixing together LEDs that emit different wavelengths of light, one could=
=20
create a white light-emitting LED, Johnson says. (White light is a mixture =
of=20
all other optical wavelengths.)=20
Johnson maintains LEDs could make a difference to the energy bill.=20
"One-third of our energy used in commercial buildings goes into lighting=20
those buildings. So anything we do to reduce the lighting bill is going to=
=20
help the energy crisis."=20
SUPER-EFFICIENT APPLIANCES
All sorts of strategies are being tried in labs all over the country.=20
Forget to turn off the iron before you drove out of town? Appliances that c=
an=20
be switched off remotely, via computer modem, are being developed by the=20
Media Lab at MIT as part of its "Kitchen Sync" project.=20
The same project is figuring out how to create electronically interconnecte=
d=20
homes in which the appliances will switch themselves on to perform=20
nonessential work -- say, washing the clothes -- only when there's no risk =
of=20
a circuit overload.=20
Super-efficient refrigerators that use "magnetic" refrigerants are being=20
tested at Ames Laboratory, a federally financed lab in Ames, Iowa.=20
Scientists there are using "magnetic cooling" methods to replace the=20
compressed gases deployed by typical refrigerators. Physicists have long=20
known that some materials get hotter when magnetized and cool off when=20
demagnetized.=20
Even today's refrigerators consume energy far more efficiently than they on=
ce=20
did.=20
Federal energy standards for refrigerators that took effect in July 2000=20
require that they burn only one-fourth as much energy as did their=20
predecessors, 25 years ago, Rosenfeld notes.=20
Even better, he adds, modern refrigerators are bigger and don't use=20
chlorofluorocarbons, chemical compounds that are believed to damage the ozo=
ne=20
layer, which shields the Earth from cancer-causing ultraviolet radiation.=
=20
"It's all just a matter of designing them properly," Rosenfeld says.=20
E-mail Keay Davidson at kdavidson@sfchronicle.com




