Customers in North Beach and at Pier 39 were affected, she said. All=20
customers had power back by 5:50 p.m. after workers replaced the splice at=
=20
the intersection of North Point and Stockton streets.




THE ENERGY CRUNCH=20
Oakland council to vote on waiving energy permits=20
Residents' solar, wind power plans for their homes now face high costs, lon=
g=20
delays Janine DeFao, Chronicle Staff Writer
Monday, May 21, 2001=20
,2001 San Francisco Chronicle=20
URL:=20
http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=3D/chronicle/archive/2001/05=
/21/M
N112477.DTL&type=3Dnews=20
Oakland -- Already seeing red over rising utility bills, Oakland residents=
=20
have found themselves mired in red tape when they have sought energy=20
alternatives such as solar power.=20
It can take up to eight weeks and cost more than $1,000 to get the required=
=20
city permits to install solar panels.=20
But the City Council is expected to change that tomorrow when it considers =
an=20
emergency ordinance, proposed by Mayor Jerry Brown, to eliminate design=20
review requirements for renewable energy installations including solar pane=
ls=20
and wind devices.=20
"Energy is an issue on everybody's plate these days. . . . We want to make =
it=20
easy for people to get their permits and get their panels," said Gary Patto=
n,=20
the city's deputy planning director.=20
Oakland officials said they know of no other city taking similar steps to=
=20
promote alternative energy generation, although cities throughout the Bay=
=20
Area and the state are increasingly looking to renewable energy sources.=20
San Francisco, for instance, is considering placing solar energy bonds on t=
he=20
November ballot that would fund installation of solar panels on municipal=
=20
property and could provide low-cost loans for homeowners and businesses to =
do=20
the same. Berkeley also is working on a loan program for renewable energy=
=20
sources for residences.=20
The Oakland measure, which would remain in effect for two years, also would=
=20
apply to businesses interested in pursuing alternative energy generation.=
=20
As Californians already hit by the state's energy crunch face the prospect =
of=20
more rolling blackouts this summer, Oakland city officials are receiving a=
=20
growing number of inquiries from residents interested in installing solar=
=20
panels, Patton said.=20
The city also has heard complaints about the cost and time it now takes to=
=20
get systems approved.=20
Gary Gerber, president of Sun Light & Power in Berkeley, said he complained=
=20
when he learned that it would cost more than $1,200 to install a solar syst=
em=20
on a home in the Montclair area. The project is on hold, awaiting the new=
=20
ordinance.=20
"The process didn't really fit our situation. . . . It's pretty cumbersome=
=20
and is the same type of process you might go through for a major remodel,"=
=20
Gerber said.=20
City officials "responded beautifully" in drafting a "solar-friendly" polic=
y,=20
he added.=20
Calvin Wong, director of building services, said the city has received a=20
dozen applications for solar panel installations in the last month -- up fr=
om=20
only a few applications before the energy crisis hit. "We anticipate a lot=
=20
more," he said.=20
Gerber said he gets five to 10 calls a day from interested customers. He ha=
s=20
done as much business in the first three months of this year as he did all =
of=20
last year, he said.=20
"I don't think solar panels have been a significant issue for (Oakland) up =
to=20
now," said Councilman Dick Spees, who backs the proposed change. "We want t=
o=20
encourage it by making it simple, direct and less costly."=20
Oakland also is exploring installing solar panels on city buildings.=20
A household solar unit -- which can heat water or produce electricity=20
directly -- can cost $10,000 to $30,000, although state rebates can reduce=
=20
the price by half. President Bush's energy plan, released last week, propos=
es=20
a 15 percent tax credit for residents who install solar panels.=20
Patton said the "main target" of Oakland's emergency ordinance was solar=20
panels, but it would apply to other "renewable energy production facilities=
,"=20
including those using wind and water.=20
Currently, design review for such installations can cost between $397 and=
=20
$1,088 and take between three and eight weeks, depending on a property's=20
location.=20
Under the proposal, design review would be waived once an owner submits=20
drawings to the city showing that the equipment installation meets certain=
=20
requirements, such as matching the pitch of a sloped roof or, if=20
freestanding, being no taller than 6 feet. For certain structures, such as=
=20
designated landmark sites, design review still would be required, but at no=
=20
cost and lasting no more than five days.=20
Building permits and inspections, costing between $85 and $170, still would=
=20
be required to make sure the additions are safe, Patton said.=20
Brown has long been considered an alternative energy advocate, pioneering=
=20
state solar and wind tax credits when he was governor.=20
E-mail Janine DeFao at jdefao@sfchronicle.com




ENERGY CRUNCH=20
Investigations=20
Power firms fueled by greed, Lockyer says=20
Out-of-state generators face multiple probes=20
Greg Lucas, Sacramento Bureau Chief
Sunday, May 20, 2001=20
,2001 San Francisco Chronicle=20
URL:=20
http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=3D/chronicle/archive/2001/05=
/20/M
N172739.DTL&type=3Dnews=20
Sacramento -- Up the road in Folsom, at the nondescript headquarters of the=
=20
Independent System Operator -- monitor-in-chief of California's energy grid=
=20
-- they have a new job: responding to more than 40 detailed subpoenas.=20
The data the ISO keeps on electricity transactions are central to the half-=
=20
dozen investigations initiated by state and federal agencies into various=
=20
parts of the state's energy mess, including possible criminal activity by=
=20
power generators.=20
"They're asking for everything and then some," a spokeswoman for the ISO,=
=20
Stephanie McCorkle, said, sighing.=20
The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, the state Public Utilities=20
Commission, the Assembly, the Senate, the state attorney general and a=20
phalanx of state and federal auditors all are boring into California's ener=
gy=20
mess.=20
The main thrust of the most significant investigations is the conduct of=20
power generators that have reaped record profits selling electricity to the=
=20
electron-starved state.=20
Although most investigators say the ISO's logs and bid records show the=20
various generators used their market share to drive up prices, the issue is=
=20
whether they did so acting collaboratively, either directly or indirectly.=
=20
Generators deny any manipulation of the market. They say their prices simpl=
y=20
reflect a lack of supply, plant breakdowns and the high cost of natural gas=
.=20
But that hasn't stopped the state from trying to prove them wrong.=20
Attorney General Bill Lockyer has been probing the actions of the generator=
s=20
since August to see if they manipulated the market or engaged in unfair=20
business practices or if their executives engaged in criminal behavior.=20
"We all feel we've been taken advantage of, been gouged," Lockyer said. "Th=
e=20
question is whether it's legal greed or illegal greed. There's no question=
=20
it's greed."=20
Lockyer is in court fighting energy companies like Reliant Energy Inc. and=
=20
Dynegy, which have refused to disclose internal company information that=20
Lockyer subpoenaed Feb. 15.=20
The power companies say they are not receiving assurances the documents=20
Lockyer wants will be kept confidential.=20
Lockyer said he hopes to complete his spadework on the generators this=20
summer.=20
The PUC also is probing whether generators timed maintenance and shutdowns =
to=20
drive up prices.=20
On Thursday, PUC President Loretta Lynch said investigators found patterns =
of=20
plant shutdowns that created "artificial shortages."=20
Lockyer insisted that "no one yet has sufficient evidence to win a civil or=
=20
criminal suit. But we're probably further along than any other investigativ=
e=20
effort."=20
Generators say they are cooperating with the investigations -- except for=
=20
worries about proprietary information becoming public -- and flatly reject=
=20
the notion they have been gaming the market or acting in concert.=20
"We naturally would take serious issue with some of those allegations," sai=
d=20
Richard Wheatley, a spokesman for Reliant Energy in Houston. "It doesn't=20
compute because we all compete against each other. We don't cooperate, shar=
e=20
information or anything of that nature. It's not only illegal but unethical=
=20
to do so."=20
Said Chuck Griffin, a Mirant Corp. spokesman: "Any patterns would exist=20
because of the rules they established long before Mirant was in California.=
"=20
A new investigation of the generators is being done also by the aptly named=
=20
Senate Select Committee to Investigate Price Manipulation in the Wholesale=
=20
Energy Market. It too is meeting resistance from generators in handing over=
=20
documents they consider confidential.=20
"Discussions thus far in that regard have been disturbing, and right now=20
we're at an impasse," said Sen. Joe Dunn, D-Santa Ana, the committee's=20
chairman.=20
Dunn's committee can only gather facts and make recommendations on new laws=
=20
if it uncovers some kind of anti-competitive activity not already covered b=
y=20
the law.=20
So far, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission is the only entity to impo=
se=20
any economic pain on generators.=20
After a probe of California's power market last summer, the commission issu=
ed=20
an order in December that created a mechanism by which generators would hav=
e=20
to justify prices above a certain level determined by the commission.=20
In March, the commission said generators had to justify $124 million in=20
charges -- or reimburse the money.=20
It also reached an $8 million settlement with AES Southland and Williams=20
Energy Marketing & Trading over power plants that were supposed to be runni=
ng=20
but weren't.=20
Critics, from Gov. Gray Davis down, say that generators owe many millions=
=20
more in refunds.=20
Several other investigations are either under way or completed.=20
The PUC is investigating whether the holding companies of Pacific Gas and=
=20
Electric, Southern California Edison and Sempra Energy in San Diego violate=
d=20
the requirement that the utility be their first spending priority.=20
The investigation came after discoveries that while PG&E and Edison were=20
accumulating huge debts buying power, they were also transferring hundreds =
of=20
millions to their parent companies.=20
Probes sparked by power crisis=20
Here's a look at some of the investigations California's power crisis has=
=20
sparked and their status:=20
Market manipulation by power generators -- The Public Utilities Commission,=
=20
attorney general and a special Senate committee are all investigating=20
allegations.=20
High prices charged by generators -- The Federal Energy Regulatory Commissi=
on=20
said in March that generators must justify $124 million in possible=20
overcharges or refund the money. The investigation is still open.=20
Investor-owned utilities transferring large sums to their holding companies=
=20
-- The PUC is examining whether any regulations were violated.=20
The flaws of electrical deregulation -- The state auditor general completed=
 a=20
report in March.=20
Audits of the utilities -- A report concluding utilities transferred millio=
ns=20
to parent companies was released in January by the PUC.=20
Price spikes in natural gas -- An Assembly committee issued its report last=
=20
week, saying El Paso Corp. manipulated the market.=20
E-mail Greg Lucas at glucas@sfchronicle.com.




Davis slams Bush's energy policy=20
He says president should ensure 'reasonable' prices=20
Tyche Hendricks, Chronicle Staff Writer
Sunday, May 20, 2001=20
,2001 San Francisco Chronicle=20
URL:=20
http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=3D/chronicle/archive/2001/05=
/20/M
N166290.DTL&type=3Dnews=20
Gov. Gray Davis blasted President Bush's energy strategy yesterday, saying =
it=20
will fail to rein in galloping energy prices and insinuating that Bush's=20
close ties to the oil industry are behind his unwillingness to regulate=20
prices.=20
Davis, in delivering the Democratic response to Bush's weekly radio address=
,=20
called on Bush to place a cap on wholesale energy prices, which, he said, a=
re=20
imperiling California's economy.=20
"I urge you to stand up to your friends in the energy business and exercise=
=20
the federal government's exclusive responsibility to ensure energy prices a=
re=20
reasonable," said Davis.=20
California consumer advocates and utility officials alike endorsed the call=
=20
for rate caps.=20
Bush has rejected such caps, although in his radio address yesterday, he=20
noted that the average family energy bill has climbed by 25 percent over th=
e=20
past three years.=20
"That's a hardship for every family," he said. "We need to act to protect=
=20
family budgets."=20
His prescription, however, was not for restricting how much energy producer=
s=20
can charge, but for increasing energy production by building more power=20
plants and drilling for oil in Alaska's Arctic National Wildlife Refuge.=20
Yesterday, Bush put into action by executive order two of his=20
recommendations, including ordering federal agencies to speed permit=20
approvals for new plant and pipeline construction. Still other proposals,=
=20
such as tax credits for hybrid vehicle purchases, will require congressiona=
l=20
action.=20
"It's time to leave behind rancorous old arguments and build a positive new=
=20
consensus," Bush said in the radio address. "With new technology, sound=20
regulation and plain good sense, we can expand our energy production while=
=20
protecting the environment."=20
Last spring, Davis said, California was paying an average of $30 for a=20
megawatt of power. By last week, the price had spiked to nearly $2,000 per=
=20
megawatt.=20
"What's going on here, pure and simple, is unconscionable price-gouging by=
=20
the big energy producers -- most of them, incidentally, located in Texas," =
he=20
said.=20
Davis criticized Bush's argument that limiting energy prices will deter=20
producers from increasing the supply of energy.=20
"That's as ridiculous as saying we need to pay dairies $300 a gallon to=20
motivate them to produce milk," he said.=20
Pacific Gas and Electric Co. officials said they are pleased with Bush's=20
emphasis on increasing electricity and natural gas generation and his call=
=20
for improving energy efficiency.=20
But a prepared statement by PG&E went on, "We continue to believe that (the=
=20
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission) must stabilize the Western market thi=
s=20
summer through circuit breakers, price caps or cost-based rates."=20
Mindy Spatt, spokeswoman for The Utility Reform Network, a San Francisco-=
=20
based consumer advocacy group, said Davis must realize Bush is not going to=
=20
implement price caps.=20
"In the absence of federal action, the governor needs to take action=20
himself," said Spatt. "He could take plants by the power of eminent domain,=
=20
impose an excess-profits tax (on energy producers), or start a buyers carte=
l,=20
where Western states get together and refuse to pay over a certain price fo=
r=20
electricity.=20
"Davis should take his own advice to the president and stand up to these=20
energy companies. The state has spent $7 billion already. He's got to put a=
=20
stop to it or they'll bleed us of every penny we have."=20
House Democrats, meanwhile, said yesterday that they intend to begin airing=
=20
television advertising in California beginning tomorrow that accuses Bush a=
nd=20
Republican lawmakers of failing to combat the rising cost of energy.=20
It is unusual for a campaign committee such as the Democratic Congressional=
=20
Campaign Committee to air political advertising more than 18 months before=
=20
elections. But the move was clearly intended to exploit consumer anger over=
=20
rising prices and rolling blackouts.=20
Chronicle news services contributed to this report. / E-mail Tyche Hendrick=
s=20
at thendricks@sfchronicle.com




Power juggling ramped up price=20
Insiders say manipulation also strained equipment=20
Christian Berthelsen, Scott Winokur, Chronicle Staff Writers
Sunday, May 20, 2001=20
,2001 San Francisco Chronicle=20
URL:=20
http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=3D/chronicle/archive/2001/05=
/20/M
N121438.DTL&type=3Dnews=20
Large power companies have driven up electricity prices in California by=20
throttling their generators up and down to create artificial shortages,=20
according to dozens of interviews with regulators, lawyers and energy=20
industry workers.=20
Those sources say the unusual maneuvers not only jacked up prices but also=
=20
wore down equipment and contributed to the record levels of plant shutdowns=
=20
that are depriving the state of much-needed electricity. The accounts are=
=20
supported by an independent review of shutdown data by The Chronicle.=20
The California Energy Commission calculates that an average of 14,990=20
megawatts of generating capacity, nearly a third of the state's total, was=
=20
unavailable each day in April because of plant shutdowns, more than four=20
times as much as a year ago.=20
Such shutdowns are the subject of increasing scrutiny as California enters=
=20
another period of high demand, the warm spring and summer months of May to=
=20
September, when electricity usage normally grows by a third.=20
Loretta Lynch, president of the California Public Utilities Commission, sai=
d=20
last week the agency has found considerable evidence of suspicious plant=20
shutdowns. And the California Independent System Operator, which manages th=
e=20
state's power grid, says plant shutdowns have now become the primary means =
of=20
constricting supply.=20
But an extensive investigation by The Chronicle has found that not only wer=
e=20
generators shut down to boost prices but these "gaming" tactics contributed=
=20
to the plants' deteriorating condition.=20
"We suspected it," said Jim MacIntosh, the manager of grid operations for t=
he=20
ISO. "It was a sure factor in driving up prices." Such swings in unit outpu=
t,=20
he said, "would only make sense in a scenario when they're trying to game=
=20
something. Otherwise, why would they do that? They're tearing their units=
=20
up."=20
Unusual phone calls=20
Operators at a San Bernardino County power plant owned by Reliant Energy In=
c.=20
say a complex plan to manipulate the California energy market began early=
=20
last year with a series of unusual telephone calls from the company's=20
headquarters in Houston.=20
According to the accounts of three plant operators, Reliant's operations=20
schedulers on the energy trading floor ordered them to repeatedly decrease,=
=20
then increase output at the 1,046-megawatt Etiwanda plant. This happened as=
=20
many as four or five times an hour. Each time the units were ramped down an=
d=20
electricity production fell, plant employees watched on a control room=20
computer screen as spot market energy prices rose. Then came the phone call=
=20
to ramp the units back up.=20
"They would tell us what to do, and we would do it," said one of the men, w=
ho=20
only agreed to speak on condition they not be identified because they fear=
=20
being fired. "Afterward, we would just sit there and watch the market=20
change."=20
The workers said frequent and large swings in electricity output began at a=
=20
number of California power plants just as the state's power crisis began in=
=20
earnest. The workers and state power authorities assert the swings were one=
=20
of the primary means of gaming the wholesale energy market.=20
"It appears the control rooms are responsive to direction from the trading=
=20
floors in Houston, rather than the reliability needs of the ISO," said Carl=
=20
Wood, a commissioner with the utilities commission who is overseeing that=
=20
agency's investigation into plant outages. "Instead of being responsive to=
=20
demands for reliability, they're responsive to demands for profitability."=
=20
Corporate denial=20
Reliant officials adamantly deny using this tactic or any other mechanism t=
o=20
game the California energy market. They and other power companies, includin=
g=20
AES Corp. and a partnership between NRG Energy Inc. and Dynegy Inc., have=
=20
asserted that skyrocketing electricity demand forced them to run aging,=20
decrepit power plants harder than ever to meet California's needs.=20
While acknowledging that the company issued changes in output levels as=20
frequently as every 10 minutes, company officials said it was done at the=
=20
instructions of the ISO to maintain supply-demand balance.=20
"As a part of routinely doing business within California and the California=
=20
market design, we are required to do that," said Kevin Frankeny, an=20
operations official with Reliant. "When the ISO (issues dispatch orders),=
=20
they dispatch on a 10-minute basis. It can go up and down many times within=
=20
an hour."=20
Frankeny said he was not aware of any instances in which Reliant schedulers=
=20
in Houston ordered dispatch changes without the ISO directing them to do it=
=20
first.=20
The ISO refused to comment on operations at any specific facility, but=20
Stephanie McCorkle, an ISO spokeswoman, said the ramping tactics were used=
=20
beyond dispatch instructions during periods of tight supply. And one of the=
=20
plant operators said the orders to vary output came independently of the gr=
id=20
managers. "ISO was not calling Reliant every 10 minutes for that," said one=
=20
of the operators. "Not for an individual unit."=20
Officials with the California attorney general's office declined to comment=
=20
on the legality of the ramping practice, citing a continuing investigation=
=20
into whether wholesale energy prices are being manipulated. One source=20
familiar with the state of various inquiries said the ramping, if proved to=
=20
have been done to drive up prices, could violate the state's unfair busines=
s=20
practices laws.=20
Invisible practice=20
How could companies such as Reliant tinker with output and not get caught?=
=20
One of the plant workers said the practice was designed to be virtually=20
invisible to regulators and grid operators.=20
When power companies bid on hourly contracts, they agree to produce a certa=
in=20
amount of electricity over the given hour. Generators are paid based on an=
=20
average of the spot market prices for that hour. By driving up the spot=20
price, they can increase their hourly profits and still produce the total=
=20
amount of energy required.=20
The plant worker said the units would be ramped down immediately after thei=
r=20
output measurement, which was performed at the top of each hour by the ISO.=
=20
Then, he said, it was brought back up as the spot market price of electrici=
ty=20
rose in response to the reduced output. By the time the ISO measured again,=
=20
the output was back at the expected level.=20
Another operator said the units were not always ramped up and down - that i=
f=20
the price reached a satisfactory level, generators would raise output and=
=20
remain at that level as long as the price was right. Other times, if the=20
price was low, output was brought down and kept down.=20
The same operator said the amount of ramping appeared to be a matter of=20
individual will of the company schedulers in Houston, with some being more=
=20
aggressive than others.=20
"What they would do, especially late at night, is if the price tanked, they=
=20
would undergenerate," an operator said. "Then, mysteriously, the price woul=
d=20
go up.=20
"Then, if the schedule was at 70 (required megawatt hours of output), they'=
d=20
say, 'Go up to 90.' That would cause the price to tank. And they'd say,=20
'Bring it down again.' "=20
Rapid changes=20
These fluctuations occurred within time spans of as little as 10 to 15=20
minutes, the operators said. But acceptable rates for bringing a unit from=
=20
minimum to maximum levels when the plant was owned by Southern California=
=20
Edison were more like 80 minutes, to avoid stressing the machinery, one of=
=20
the workers said. Moreover, they were typically run at constant levels, whi=
ch=20
also reduced wear and tear.=20
"They were basically ramping up as fast as they can, and then slamming the=
=20
brakes on," said one of the operators. "They were increasing the fatigue on=
=20
the units."=20
ISO officials say they changed market operations last fall to crack down on=
=20
gaming tactics, including instituting a so-called 10-minute market, rather=
=20
than the hourly market, so that it could be more easily detected when=20
companies were withholding power.=20
But the ISO says generator outages have now become the primary tactic in=20
driving up energy prices.=20
A computer analysis by The Chronicle of shutdown data over a recent 39-day=
=20
period shows Reliant and three other generating companies topped the list o=
f=20
plant shutdowns. Reliant also represented the largest amount of wattage los=
t=20
among those companies.=20
Plants owned by Reliant, AES, Mirant Corp. and Duke Energy Inc. accounted f=
or=20
more than half of the state's unplanned shutdowns, even though their=20
generating capacity was no more than 25 percent of the state's total capaci=
ty=20
from all sources.=20
Reliant, one of California's largest and most profitable out-of-state=20
generators, reported 319 shutdowns during the period in March and April. It=
=20
was followed by Mirant Corp. of Atlanta (310), AES Corp. of Arlington, Va.=
=20
(278) and Duke Energy North America of Charlotte, N.C. (261).=20
Reliant's unplanned shutdowns deprived the system of more than 53,000=20
megawatts over the 40-day period, an average of 1,368 per day - enough powe=
r=20
for 1.4 million homes for one hour.=20
Its Ormond Beach plant in Oxnard, with one generating unit down for 26 days=
,=20
accounted for more than 30,000 of those missed megawatts. However, an=20
operator who worked in that plant said the outages there appeared to be the=
=20
result of legitimate equipment failures.=20
Reliant says there are valid reasons for its plants now to be in need of=20
repair. They are old: At 48, Etiwanda is the oldest of Reliant's five=20
California plants. And the company says routine maintenance was deferred so=
=20
the plants could remain in service during times of high summer demand.=20
But the operators said the issue is not so clear-cut. One problem at=20
Etiwanda, a tube leak, had been present for about a month and was previousl=
y=20
reported to management, they said, but it had not deteriorated much, it was=
=20
operating at full capacity and there was no immediate need to take the unit=
=20
offline because of the problem.=20
Moreover, at the time of the shutdown, the ISO had expressly asked Reliant =
to=20
keep the unit online, the operators said. Richard Wheatley, a spokesman for=
=20
Reliant, denied that any Reliant unit was taken offline for unnecessary=20
maintenance.=20
Ramping may be rampant=20
Sources say Reliant was not alone in using the ramping practice. A source=
=20
familiar with the state utilities commission investigation said output logs=
=20
obtained from AES' Alamitos plant also reflected production fluctuations. A=
nd=20
an operator who has worked at the El Segundo plant co-owned by NRG and Dyne=
gy=20
said the practice was used there, although less frequently. The scheduling=
=20
calls came from Dynegy's trading floor in Houston, rather than NRG in=20
Minneapolis, he said.=20
Steve Stengel, a spokesman for Dynegy, said changes in output at El Segundo=
=20
were a normal function of changing demand levels throughout the day, and=20
denied the company was engaged in gaming the California market.=20
In a May 2000 report, the California Energy Commission cited Reliant's=20
Etiwanda plant, as well as the Alamitos and El Segundo plants, as some of t=
he=20
"major beneficiaries of high real-time prices" that spring.=20
One way to obtain those high prices, the plant workers said, was the simple=
=20
method of demanding a sky-high price and refusing to deliver power if that=
=20
price was not met.=20
On one occasion, one operator said, Reliant ordered a unit at Etiwanda to b=
e=20
shut off because the ISO would not meet the price of $1,000 per megawatt=20
hour, even though the legal price cap at the time was $750.=20
"The operator said, 'It's our unit, shut it off,' " the source said.=20
