Power Crisis May Can
Northwest Aluminum=20
By Robert Guy Matthews=20
?=20
05/21/2001=20
The Wall Street Journal=20
Page A1=20
(Copyright (c) 2001, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.)=20
PITTSBURGH -- The list of victims of California's botched power-deregulatio=
n=20
plan keeps growing.=20
When California's electricity shortage surfaced last fall, it caused spot=
=20
prices of electricity to skyrocket all along the West Coast. Some aluminum=
=20
companies profited by temporarily closing their massive smelters in the=20
Pacific Northwest and selling back their electricity to the spot market or =
to=20
the Bonneville Power Administration, the region's biggest power provider.=
=20
The aluminum industry, which produces nearly 40% of the nation's output in=
=20
the states of Oregon, Washington and Montana, commands a huge amount of=20
electricity, enough to power Seattle daily. Closing the smelters freed up a=
=20
lot of power and significantly reduced Bonneville's reliance on the=20
electricity spot market.=20
But Bonneville now wants the 10 smelters in the region to stay closed for t=
wo=20
years; business executives, economists and union leaders are just now=20
assessing the economic impact of the plan. And for the most part, things=20
don't look good for the small Pacific Northwest towns whose livelihoods=20
revolve around aluminum.=20
For the aluminum companies, closing plants isn't such a bad thing, at least=
=20
in the short term. Besides getting a big chunk of cash from Bonneville, the=
=20
closures will cut nearly 5% of the world's aluminum smelting capacity. Alco=
a=20
Inc., Pittsburgh, the world's leading aluminum producer, says it's closing=
=20
its Ferndale, Wash., smelter, idling 270,000 metric tons, or 7% of its annu=
al=20
capacity.=20
With that much aluminum off the market, prices, once expected to drop amid =
a=20
slowing economy, have instead firmed and are expected to rise. Pechiney SA =
of=20
France, the world's third-largest aluminum maker, expects prices to jump at=
=20
least 11% by the end of the year as a result of supply-side bottlenecks.=20
Current spot prices for aluminum hover around 69 cents a pound. Alcan Inc. =
of=20
Montreal, the second-largest aluminum maker in the world, says it expects=
=20
more growth and better profits from many of its operations, including its=
=20
specialty-packaging business, rolling mills and production of primary=20
aluminum. Meanwhile, producers in India said they plan to take advantage of=
=20
the bottleneck in the U.S. by boosting exports.=20
Outside the Pacific Northwest, "existing smelters in the U.S. are pretty mu=
ch=20
operating at capacity," says Michael F. Gambardella, metals analyst for J.P=
.=20
Morgan Securities Inc. "The problems in the Pacific Northwest have kept=20
aluminum prices relatively stable despite the current period of weak demand=
=20
for aluminum. The icing on the cake will be when the U.S. economy starts to=
=20
recover. You will see aluminum prices skyrocket."=20
For companies using aluminum as a raw material, rising prices may become=20
another burden, just as labor and energy costs and dwindling revenue damp=
=20
profits. But the biggest victims will be the rural towns in the Pacific=20
Northwest whose economies have relied on aluminum since after the Great=20
Depression, when the U.S. government supplied cheap power to run smelers in=
=20
hopes of easing high unemployment.=20
Economists believe that if aluminum plants close for two years, they will=
=20
likely stay closed. Operating aluminum smelters isn't like opening or closi=
ng=20
a 7-Eleven. It costs a lot of money to shut the metal-making operations dow=
n=20
and then even more money to reboot the entire operation. This is why alumin=
um=20
smelters and similar factories run 24 hours a day.=20
Additionally, the way that the smelting operations are configured, aluminum=
=20
companies rack up losses if the plants operate at low capacities. And=20
remaining open isn't much of an option after Bonneville signaled that power=
=20
rates will rise sharply in October, when current contracts with the aluminu=
m=20
companies expire. Sharply higher rates will make aluminum production=20
unprofitable.=20
For now, Alcoa said it will not immediately lay off the 900 employees at th=
e=20
shuttered Ferndale plant, primarily because Bonneville agreed to reimburse=
=20
Alcoa for employee wages and benefits.=20
Still, the news of plant closings is sending shock waves through communitie=
s=20
such as Goldendale, Wash., a small town on the banks of the Columbia River.=
=20
Together, Goldendale Aluminum Co. and Northwest Aluminum Co. employ about=
=20
1,300 people, more than one-third of the immediate area's working populatio=
n.=20
Those aluminum jobs pay about $58,000 a year in salary and benefits. "The=
=20
jobs created by these industries are the lifeblood of our communities," say=
s=20
Mark Sigfrinius, Goldendale's mayor. "They cannot be written off."=20
To ease the pain, Bonneville is hoping that it can strike a deal so that th=
e=20
aluminum makers in the region will take payments received for shutting down=
=20
and use that money either to retrain the work force or to provide a lump-su=
m=20
payment to help them make it through the two years. But the United=20
Steelworkers of America, representing 6,000 workers in the affected Oregon,=
=20
Montana and Washington region, says that its skilled work force would=20
probably just leave the region and find work elsewhere under the BPA plan.=
=20
"The union is jumping up and down about this," says David Foster, a=20
negotiator for the union. "We intend to make absolutely sure that money com=
es=20
to the union workers. Two years is a long time."






